  "prompt": "According to the first law of motion, external force stops a body in uniform motion. What force do I have if I stop a rolling pin.?",
  "response": "When you stop a rolling pin, you are applying an **external force** to it. This force acts in the opposite direction to the pin's motion, causing it to decelerate and eventually come to rest. This is consistent with **Newton's First Law of Motion**, which states that an object in motion will remain in motion unless acted upon by an external force.\n\nThe specific force you apply to stop the rolling pin is likely a combination of **frictional force** (between your hand and the pin) and perhaps a **normal force** (if you press down on it). These forces work together to counteract the pin's motion and bring it to a stop.",
